ðŸŽ® IF score > 100 â†’ You win!

Life is full of IF situations!

In code:

if (condition)
{
    // Do this when condition is TRUE
}

Like a fork in the road:
- Condition true? Take this path!
- Condition false? Skip this path!

if (temperature > 30)
{
    Console.WriteLine("It's hot!");
}

Think: IF statements let your program choose different actions based on conditions!

coderExample:
// BASIC IF STATEMENT
int age = 20;

if (age >= 18)
{
    Console.WriteLine("You can vote!");
}
// This runs because 20 >= 18 is TRUE

// IF WITH FALSE CONDITION
int score = 50;

if (score > 100)
{
    Console.WriteLine("You win!");  // Doesn't run (50 not > 100)
}
Console.WriteLine("Game over");  // Always runs

// MULTIPLE STATEMENTS IN IF
int temperature = 35;

if (temperature > 30)
{
    Console.WriteLine("It's hot!");
    Console.WriteLine("Drink water!");
    Console.WriteLine("Stay in shade!");
}
// All three run because 35 > 30

// PRACTICAL EXAMPLES

// Password checker
string password = "secret123";

if (password == "secret123")
{
    Console.WriteLine("Access granted!");
}

// Discount eligibility
int purchaseAmount = 150;

if (purchaseAmount >= 100)
{
    Console.WriteLine("You qualify for free shipping!");
}

// Speed limit
int speed = 75;
int limit = 65;

if (speed > limit)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Speeding! Slow down!");
    int over = speed - limit;
    Console.WriteLine($"You're {over} mph over the limit");
}

// Even/odd checker
int number = 8;

if (number % 2 == 0)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"{number} is even");
}

